The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Saturday, August 07, 2004 				 Ranbaxy plans high-end hospitals
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Aug. 6: Ranbaxy, one of Indias premier pharmaceutical companies, has launched a Rs 1,100-crore investment plan for healthcare in the countrys north.																								The company wants to expand in a big way into the related healthcare sector where its core expertise in research and drug manufacturing will be a major advantage. It plans to provide world-class healthcare to patients from the higher income groups.																								Fortis Healthcare Limited, a Ranbaxy group company, plans to build six hospitals in the national capital region over the next five years and four in Punjab.																								The first of the Fortis hospitals will be built in Noida at Rs 100 crore. The Fortis Jessaram hospital on Pusa Road will come next. The others will be in different parts of Delhi and Gurgaon.																								Each hospital will have multi-speciality capabilities  such as neurosciences, oncology and cardiology  and be a centre of excellence in at least one super-speciality.																								The idea is to provide personalised service with a human touch and international quality at affordable prices, the company said. Ranbaxy hopes patients will come from across India and abroad.																								Fortis aims to establish an integrated health delivery system in India offering comprehensive health services addressing all needs from minor ailments to high-end surgical procedures, a company statement said today.																								All hospitals across the region will be linked through a strong IT backbone and high-end IT services will be available, it said.
